{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17621504","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17621504"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:54:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:54:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16748"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16748","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16748"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.71,0.04,0.14,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9439"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66764"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9439","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9439"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16748"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52218"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7180"},{"type":"tags","id":"8505"},{"type":"tags","id":"10346"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22311"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22314"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66764","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66764"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the arachnoid mater?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Forms the denticulate ligaments","Contains cerebrospinal fluid in the subarachnoid space","Continues inferiorly as the filum terminale","Is a vascular membrane closely investing the central nervous system","Forms the tough, outermost protective layer"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe arachnoid mater is the middle layer of the meninges, situated between the dura mater and pia mater. \u003Cstrong\u003EContains cerebrospinal fluid in the subarachnoid space\u003C/strong\u003E is correct, as the space between the arachnoid and pia mater (subarachnoid space) contains cerebrospinal fluid, blood vessels, and arachnoid trabeculae.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Edenticulate ligaments\u003C/strong\u003E are actually extensions of the pia mater that anchor the spinal cord to the dura mater, not the arachnoid mater.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Efilum terminale\u003C/strong\u003E is a fibrous extension of the pia mater that extends from the conus medullaris to the coccyx, not a continuation of the arachnoid mater.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Evascular membrane closely investing the central nervous system\u003C/strong\u003E describes the pia mater, which is the innermost meningeal layer that follows all the contours of the brain and spinal cord and contains blood vessels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etough, outermost protective layer\u003C/strong\u003E describes the dura mater, which is the thick and tough outer layer of the meninges.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The arachnoid mater is the middle meningeal layer containing cerebrospinal fluid in the subarachnoid space.","The arachnoid mater is avascular and forms a loose covering over the brain and spinal cord.","The subarachnoid space contains cerebrospinal fluid, blood vessels, and trabeculae connecting to the pia mater."],"references":["Lu S, Brusic A, Gaillard F. Arachnoid Membranes: Crawling Back into Radiologic Consciousness. AJNR Am J Neuroradiol. 2022 Feb;43(2):167-175. doi: 10.3174/ajnr.A7309. Epub 2021 Oct 28. PMID: 34711549; PMCID: PMC8985673.","Ghannam JY, Al Kharazi KA. Neuroanatomy, Cranial Meninges. [Updated 2023 Jul 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK539882/","Adeeb N, Deep A, Griessenauer CJ, Mortazavi MM, Watanabe K, Loukas M, Tubbs RS, Cohen-Gadol AA. The intracranial arachnoid mater : a comprehensive review of its history, anatomy, imaging, and pathology. Childs Nerv Syst. 2013 Jan;29(1):17-33. doi: 10.1007/s00381-012-1910-x. Epub 2012 Sep 8. PMID: 22961357."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52218"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16748"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52218","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52218"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-02T00:11:48+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-02T00:12:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9439"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66764"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tag